	<h1>Judith's Pick: Late July 2013</h1>

	<h2 class="post-subtitle">
					30/07/2013
						- 												
	</h2>

	
		    <div class="attribute-long">
		
<p>Here below, a list of recent developments in agricultural research.</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Scientific development in African countries</b></p><p>INASP presents findings from a bibliometric analysis of the most productive African countries in Scopus between 1996 and 2009. Changes in the scientific research output and comparisons with global patterns across 27 scientific knowledge domains are illustrated. It details publication patterns over ten years, the number of research papers produced per year per country, the nature of international collaboration in multi-author publications, etc. Strengths and weakness are identified which can be used to inform future decision-making processes.</p><p><a href="http://www.inasp.info/en/publications/details/113/" target="_self">http://www.inasp.info/en/publications/details/113/</a></p><p>(INASP, 20/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>The Atlas of African Agriculture Research and Development </b></p><p>The preview of the <i>Atlas of African Agriculture Research and Development</i>, published by IFPRI in 2013, is part of a wide-ranging <i>e-Atlas initiative</i> that will showcase a variety of spatial data, tools, and services generated by R&amp;D practitioners working in Africa. This preview features a number of maps and data tables related to topics such as Africa’s public agriculture R&amp;D investments and its agriculture research pool (using ASTI data), and the footprint of agriculture, environmental and economic constraints and opportunities.</p><p><a href="http://harvestchoice.org/labs/revealing-agriculture%E2%80%99s-place-africa-e-atlas-initiative" target="_self">http://harvestchoice.org/labs/revealing-agriculture%E2%80%99s-place-africa-e-atlas-initiative</a></p><p>(HarvestChoice, 09/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Launch of the Cassava Mechanisation and Agro-processing Project (CAMAP)</b></p><p>Coordinated by the African Agricultural Technology Foundation (AATF), the Cassava Mechanisation and Agro-processing Project (CAMAP) will help with the upgrading and expanding of traditional planting, harvesting and processing techniques, and develop competitive cassava commodity value.</p><p><a href="http://goo.gl/RjfiD" target="_self">http://goo.gl/RjfiD</a></p><p>(AATF, 04/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>How the future demand for food should be met </b><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p>Two recent working papers by the World Resources Institute (WRI) are the first in a new series leading to the <i>World Resources Report 2013-14: Creating a Sustainable Food Future</i>. One paper, ‘The great balancing act’ assesses the scope of the challenge posed by the need to feed a growing population in the near-future while reducing pressure on the environment. Another paper, ‘Reducing food loss and waste’, explains how efforts to reduce postharvest losses and waste perform against each of the sustainable food future criteria. <a href="http://www.worldresourcesreport.org/" target="_self">http://www.worldresourcesreport.org/</a></p><p>(WRI, 01/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Sustainable intensification in agriculture: premises and policies</b></p><p>The Food Climate Research Network (FCRN) and the Oxford Martin Programme on the Future of Food, UK, have jointly published a report entitled: <i>Sustainable intensification in agriculture. Navigating a course through competing food system priorities</i>. Based on discussions held at a workshop in 2012, the report tries to map the concepts behind the idea of ‘sustainable intensification’ (SI) and to identify areas where further work is needed. Ultimately, the report argues the case for a more ‘systems’ oriented approach to decision making. More recently, a paper was published on the subject.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://www.fcrn.org.uk/fcrn/publications/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies" target="_self">http://www.fcrn.org.uk/fcrn/publications/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies</a> and <a href="http://www.futureoffood.ox.ac.uk/news/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies" target="_self">http://www.futureoffood.ox.ac.uk/news/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies</a></p><p>(FCRN and Future of Food, 04/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Investigating how insect larvae could become the basis for future animal feeds</b></p><p>The three-year PROteINSECT project, launched early 2013, is led by the UK based Food and Environment Research Agency (FERA) focuses its research efforts on insect larvae not only for their ability to grow rapidly on a range of organic wastes, but also because there is already considerable expertise in their rearing in countries such as Mali, Ghana and China.</p><p><a href="http://www.stir.ac.uk/news/news-archive/13/07/animal-feed-study/name-48153-en.html" target="_self">http://www.stir.ac.uk/news/news-archive/13/07/animal-feed-study/name-48153-en.html</a></p><p>(University of Stirling, 08/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Realising Farmers' Rights to Crop Genetic Resources: Success Stories and Best Practices</b></p><p>This book provides decision-makers and practitioners with a conceptual framework for understanding farmers’ rights and success stories showing how each of the elements of farmers' rights can be realised in practice.&nbsp; Note: this book is not free.</p><p><a href="http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415643849/#description" target="_self">http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415643849/#description</a>&nbsp;</p><p>(Routledge, 18/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Mining the wealth of the world's seed banks</b></p><p>In a recent Comment in <i>Nature</i>, Cornell University plant geneticist Susan McCouch and colleagues says that the biodiversity stored in plant gene banks coupled with advances in genetics and plant breeding may hold the keys for meeting the challenge of climate change, soil degradation and water and land shortages.</p><p><a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-07/cu-tft070513.php" target="_self">http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-07/cu-tft070513.php</a> and <a href="http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v499/n7456/full/499023a.html?WT.ec_id=NATURE-20130704" target="_self">http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v499/n7456/full/499023a.html?WT.ec_id=NATURE-20130704</a></p><p>(Eurekalert, 05/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Breeding better barley for Ethiopia's staple bread</b></p><p>A team of plant breeders led by Fetien Abay of Mekelle University in Ethiopia and Åsmund Bjørnstad of the Norwegian University of Life Sciences followed an approach called participatory plant breeding to select the varieties of barley most adapted for the preparation of injera (a very popular bread in Ethiopia). They found that, if cooked in the traditional way, injera prepared with barley from a variety that is a cross between the Himblil and Saesa variety, scored very high among the Ethiopian tasters.</p><p>Editors’ comment: Production of Teff, one of the earliest plants to be domesticated and the grain which is traditionally used in Ethiopia for the preparation of injera, while no aggregated stats exists, is almost two times that of barley in Ethiopia (FAO stats, HarvestChoice). It is also high in dietary fibre, iron, and provides calcium and protein. A question for scientists/breeders and policymakers to ponder, is while the cheaper injera made from barley is comparable tastewise: How does it compare on nutritional content? Another issue is that teff is adapted to numerous environments; drought stressed and water logged. Are the barley varieties similarly adapted?</p><p><a href="https://www.crops.org/story/2013/jul/tue/breeding-better-barley-for-ethiopias-staple-bread/" target="_self">https://www.crops.org/story/2013/jul/tue/breeding-better-barley-for-ethiopias-staple-bread/</a></p><p>(Crop Science Society of America, 02/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Five Pacific island countries to revive and unlock the potential of bele, an indigenous vegetable</b></p><p>Papua New Guinea, New Caledonia, Vanuatu, Solomon Islands and Fiji will address together priority research needs to revive bele (<i>Abelmoschus manihot</i>, also known as aibika or slippery cabbage) a neglected but nutritious native crop. Bele is known to have medicinal properties, requires low maintenance, and some varieties are tolerant to drought, other to pests. Unfortunately, some 30 varieties of bele were noted to have been lost over the years in Papua New Guinea in the early 1990s.</p><p><a href="http://goo.gl/9nsJJ" target="_self">http://goo.gl/9nsJJ</a></p><p>(SPC, 02/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Traditional use of medicinal plants in south-central Zimbabwe: review and perspectives</b></p><p>Alfred Maroyi of the Department of Biodiversity at the University of Limpopo’s School of Molecular and Life Sciences, South Africa compiles and assesses information on Zimbabwe’s medicinal plants and their traditional uses. Maroyi identifies several research gaps and according to him, ‘validating the correlations of the ethno-medicinal uses, bioactive substances, biological and pharmacological effects’ is of special importance and should be&nbsp; the primary task for future research.</p><p><a href="http://www.ethnobiomed.com/content/pdf/1746-4269-9-31.pdf" target="_self">www.ethnobiomed.com/content/pdf/1746-4269-9-31.pdf</a></p><p>(<i>Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine</i> 9:31, 2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>South Africa launches its indigenous knowledge recording system</b></p><p>The National Recordal System (NRS) of the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR), South Africa will document and record IK through the National Indigenous Knowledge Management System (NIKMAS) information and communication technology platform. It will record African IK in its original oral format, linking it to a complex metadata schema to provide the necessary mechanisms for both positive and defensive (legal) protection.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://www.csir.co.za/enews/2013_jun/01.html" target="_self">http://www.csir.co.za/enews/2013_jun/01.html</a></p><p>(CSIR, 18/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Salt tolerant taro varieties identified in Palau</b></p><p>Three varieties of taro (Dungersuul, Dirrubong, Kirang) were identified as salt-tolerant in one of the research trials carried out in Palau. The research is led by Dr Aurora Del Rosario, Researcher/Extension Specialist of the Palau Community Colleges Cooperative Research and Extension in Koror. Research also included treatments which looked at impact of fertilizers and manure.</p><p><a href="http://bit.ly/10maVFo" target="_self">http://bit.ly/10maVFo</a></p><p>(Marianas Variety, 26/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Development of PNG’s galip nut industry</b></p><p>A new project of Papua New Guinea’s National Agricultural research Institute (NARI) aims to develop the island’s galip nut (or nangae - <i>Canarium indicum</i>) industry and its domestic and international markets. The project will distribute seedlings of improved varieties of the nut tree, research and disseminate better drying and other production systems, develop standards and policies that are more adapted to industrialisation.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://www.nari.org.pg/node/272" target="_self">http://www.nari.org.pg/node/272</a></p><p>(NARI PNG, 05/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Interplanting small-scale timber plantations with native agroforestry species in Solomon </b></p><p>This project shows that village-owned plantations of high-value timber trees, mainly teak (<i>Tectona grandis</i>) and mahogany (<i>Swietenia macrophylla</i>) in the Solomon Islands can benefit from interplanting with the indigenous tree <i>Flueggea flexuosa</i> and other tree species native to the Pacific region. The rationale behind this interplanting is that commercial plantations must always be thinned and removing young timbers trees that cannot be sold offers no practical advantages. However, thinning the plantations by only removing indigenous tree species can benefit the villagers in many ways: with fruits and other tree products, firewood, and construction materials.</p><p><a href="http://aciar.gov.au/publication/FR2013-09" target="_self">http://aciar.gov.au/publication/FR2013-09</a></p><p>(ACIAR, 26/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Testing a low-tech cooling system for dairy farmers in rural Ethiopia</b></p><p>The cooling system sets out to improve the quality of evening milk and thus the income of the farmers. The solar powered system makes ice at milk collection centres, which the farmer collects and brings home during the day to cool the evening milk before bringing it to the collection point the following day. The system is designed to work on solar and electricity grids.</p><p><a href="http://lives-ethiopia.org/2013/06/24/low-tech-cooling/" target="_self">http://lives-ethiopia.org/2013/06/24/low-tech-cooling/</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Genetics, genomics and gene modification: What does the future of animal production hold? </b></p><p>According to Professor David Hume it is very unlikely that existing genetic variation in animals will continue to generate the rate of gain in size or offspring number obtained in the past. Hume believes that ‘transgenesis’ (genetic engineering) to produce desired traits is. He concludes that sustainable gains in productivity of livestock will only be achieved if governments recognise that the required research is a ‘public good’, and re-enter and re-engage with the livestock research sector with substantial investment.’</p><p><a href="http://bit.ly/1agTNqX" target="_self">http://bit.ly/1agTNqX</a></p><p>(BBSRC, 08/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Vitamin A rich, open-pollinated maize varieties released in Nigeria </b></p><p>The first generation of pro-vitamin A-rich orange open-pollinated maize varieties was released in June 2013 by the Institute for Agricultural Research (IAR) in Nigeria.</p><p><a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201307081085.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201307081085.html</a></p><p>(AllAfrica, 08/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Gene that controls multi-herbicide resistance offers prospect of better weed control </b></p><p>BBSRC-funded scientists at the Universities of York and Durham in the UK have discovered a gene that plays a key role in controlling multi-herbicide resistance (MHR) in black-grass and rye-grass. Chemicals that inhibit this gene can be used to make weed killers effective against resistant weeds.&nbsp; Is balk-grass and rye-grass a problem for cereal growers in ACP countries?</p><p><a href="http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/news/food-security/2013/130708-n-gene-discovery-aid-weed-control.aspx" target="_self">http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/news/food-security/2013/130708-n-gene-discovery-aid-weed-control.aspx</a></p><p>(BBSRC, 08/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>The Intergovernmental Technical Panel on Soils (ITPS): A new global scientific authority</b></p><p>ITPS was launched at the first Plenary Assembly of the Global Soil Partnership held at FAO Headquarters, held 11-12 June 2013. The ITPS is composed of 27 top soil experts representing all the regions of the world. The main function of the ITPS is to provide scientific and technical advice and guidance on global soil issues to the Global Soil Partnership.</p><p><a href="http://www.fao.org/globalsoilpartnership/highlights/detail/en/c/177933/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/globalsoilpartnership/highlights/detail/en/c/177933/</a></p><p>(FAO, 13/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>OrganicDataNetwork for better European organic market information</b></p><p>The project ‘Data network for better European organic market information’ (OrganicDataNetwork) aims to increase the transparency of the European organic food market. The network will focus on organic market data in terms of: end-users needs; public and private bodies that collect and process data; methodologies; accessibility and quality improvement; etc. A forum has been established to facilitate interactive information exchange.</p><p><a href="http://aims.fao.org/community/blogs/data-network-better-european-organic-market-information-organicdatanetwork" target="_self">http://aims.fao.org/community/blogs/data-network-better-european-organic-market-information-organicdatanetwork</a></p><p>(AIMS, 20/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>International guidelines on securing sustainable small-scale fisheries</b></p><p>The FAO guidelines are relevant to small-scale fisheries in marine and inland waters and cover fishing as well as related post-harvest and upstream activities. The Guidelines complement and support, in addition to the Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries (CCRF), other international instruments and commitments.</p><p><a href="http://www.fao.org/fishery/ssf/guidelines/en" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/fishery/ssf/guidelines/en</a></p><p>(SSF FAO, 25/05/2013)</p><p><b>Pushing for efficiency in fish and vegetable integrated farming in Uganda</b></p><p>Entrepreneur Charles Mulamata from Uganda describes his efforts to build an efficient aquaponics system that is low-cost and makes good use of local resources. He explains what construction material were used, which vegetable and fish species work best together, and how he has addressed the main challenges facing the adoption of the technology in the country. He created the African Aquaponics Association to promote the system. <a href="http://www.theworld.org/2013/06/pushing-super-efficient-fish-veggie-farming-in-uganda/" target="_self">http://www.theworld.org/2013/06/pushing-super-efficient-fish-veggie-farming-in-uganda/</a></p><p>(PRI <i>The World</i>, 27/06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>South-South collaboration:&nbsp; Participatory Market Chain Approach (PMCA)</b></p><p>The Participatory Market Chain Approach (PMCA) is an effort to facilitate South-South collaboration. The Andean experiences with the PMCA were shared with Ugandan R&amp;D professionals and market chain actors in 2005-2007, and how the approach was applied successfully on the potato, sweet potato, tomato and hot pepper market chains in Uganda.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://www.cipotato.org/publications/pdf/006073.pdf" target="_self">http://www.cipotato.org/publications/pdf/006073.pdf</a></p><p>(CIP, 2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Contemplating the Brazilian dilemma: abundant grain and inadequate storage</b></p><p>Using GIS software to map the coordinates of commercial, cooperative and private grain storage facilities, this research quantified the shortage in storage and identified under-served areas to help planning policy locate appropriate locations for new warehouses. The consequences of the shortage are losses and waste, mainly from the discarded grain left on the fields after harvest and from poor transportation infrastructure. <a href="http://news.aces.illinois.edu/news/contemplating-brazilian-dilemma-abundant-graininadequate-storage" target="_self">http://news.aces.illinois.edu/news/contemplating-brazilian-dilemma-abundant-graininadequate-storage</a></p><p>(University of Illinois, 09/07/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Postharvest agriculture in changing climates: its importance to African smallholder farmers</b></p><p>This study describes typical grain postharvest systems in east and southern Africa and discusses the likely impacts of different climate change trends on postharvest activities, assets and human well-being outcomes. To strengthen the adaptive capacity of postharvest systems, factors such as its omission from training curricula, innovation system challenges, the policy bias towards pre-harvest agricultural spending, the dominance of maize in the food system must be addressed. The article is not free.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12571-013-0262-z" target="_self">http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12571-013-0262-z</a>&nbsp;</p><p>(<i>Food security</i>, Vol. 5, Iss. 3, 06/2013)</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Food (In)Security Conference: International and Trans-disciplinary perspectives</b></p><p>Dates: 16 October 2013</p><p>Venue: University of Warwick, UK</p><p>Call for abstracts deadline: 31 July 2013</p><p><a href="http://www.fcrn.org.uk/events/foodinsecurity-conference-international-and-trans-disciplinary-perspectives" target="_self">www.fcrn.org.uk/events/foodinsecurity-conference-international-and-trans-disciplinary-perspectives</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>On-the-Job Research Capacity Building for Sustainable Agriculture in Developing Countries (OJCB)</b></p><p>Deadline: 10 August 2013</p><p>UNU-ISP will support capacity building projects proposed and implemented by leading scientists (host scientists) who are engaged in research related to sustainable agriculture (including forestry and fisheries) in developing countries, under the responsibility of a host institution. The programme mainly consists of capacity building through on-the-job training (OJT) for young researchers in developing countries (trainees).</p><p><a href="http://isp.unu.edu/news/2013/ojcb-programme.html" target="_self">http://isp.unu.edu/news/2013/ojcb-programme.html</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Programme for Emerging Agricultural Research Leaders</b></p><p>Deadline: 30 September 2013</p><p>The Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation seeks proposals for agricultural research with the potential to increase the sustainable productivity of smallholder farmers in developing countries. With this call, it is looking for projects led by MSc and PhD scientists at national agricultural research institutions and universities in sub-Saharan Africa, working in collaboration with other researchers internationally (either within Africa or beyond the continent).</p><p><a href="http://www.gatesfoundation.org/How-We-Work/General-Information/Grant-Opportunities/Program-for-Emerging-Agricultural-Research-Leaders" target="_self">http://www.gatesfoundation.org/How-We-Work/General-Information/Grant-Opportunities/Program-for-Emerging-Agricultural-Research-Leaders</a></p>
	    </div>
	
	
	
